<subSubSection id="7FDF8CBDFF85FF93FF19127F23FBFDE4" pageId="13" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="377ADF36FF85FF93FF19127F23FBFDE4" blockId="13.[113,764,282,530]" pageId="13" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF85FF93FF19127F2193FEC4" box="[151,206,283,306]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="58">Notes</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF85FF93FF63127F20D8FEC4" box="[237,389,282,306]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="borealis">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF85FF93FF63127F20D8FEC4" box="[237,389,282,306]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="58">Beguea borealis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the type specimen from the Forêt d’Ampitiliantsambo within the Montagne des Français massif (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF85FF93FEDC123E20C9FE84" box="[338,404,346,370]" captionStart="Fig. 4" captionStartId="6.[136,163,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[136,786,276,1300]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 4. – Geographic distribution of Begueo opetolo Capuron (circles), B. birkinshowii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (stars), B. boreolis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (diamond), B. tsorotononensis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (squares) and B. turkii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (triangles), mapped on the bioclimatic zones of Madagascar (after CORNET, 1974; see SCHATZ, 2000)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888183/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="58">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). It can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="F0C5A4B5FF85FF93FD6B123F21E0FE64" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="58" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="apetala">
<emphasis id="05B10324FF85FF93FD6B123F21E0FE64" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="58">B. apetala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with which it shares conduplicate leaflets that are usually folded along the midvein in pressed material, by its leaflets with a symmetrical base, the margins flat and minutely thickened but not revolute (vs leaflets with a distinctly asymmetrical base and strongly revolute margins) (
<figureCitation id="AFFEC3B3FF85FF93FDD6129E23C5FDE4" box="[600,664,506,530]" captionStart="Fig. 8" captionStartId="12.[136,163,1890,1909]" captionTargetBox="[233,1384,276,1855]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[233,1384,276,1855]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 8. – Begueo boreolis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry. A. Flowering branch; B. Leaflet (lower surface); C. Portion of inflorescence axis; D. Two flowers (one with filaments only partially expanded); E. Detail of flower at anthesis. [Rondrionoivo et ol. 1163, P]. [Drawing: R. L. Andriamiarisoa]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888191/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="58">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
